                <note rend="inline" type="source">723.2515/3308: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Peru</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Moore</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lima</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-03-20T20:00:00-05:00"
                            >March 20, 1929—8 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 10:32 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>40. Today Ambassador Figueroa notified me that the Chilean engineers would reach
                    Arica today or tomorrow. The Peruvian engineers will leave Lima on the morning
                    of March 22 by airplane for Arica.</p>
                <p>I believe the Tacna-Arica question will be practically settled if a suitable port
                    with proper railroad connections can and will be constructed by Chile for Peru
                    at either place suggested by Chile, and if President Hoover will consent to
                    present the agreement as his proposed solution.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Moore</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
